{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775859163865,"sessionID":"ses_2868bf733ffe4397rY07cpTBSx","part":{"id":"prt_d79744b20001akQlJ7p1sXqaoX","messageID":"msg_d79743d9e001A78bM9UdGIV2j6","sessionID":"ses_2868bf733ffe4397rY07cpTBSx","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-009: Router HTTP 反向代理核心 - Delta Specification\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-009  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: \n10: Implement the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality in `pkg/router` to route invocation traffic to sandbox pods. The Router serves as the edge gateway for AgentCube, accepting HTTP requests from clients, resolving sessions to sandbox endpoints via the session store, and reverse-proxying traffic to the appropriate sandbox pods. It integrates with the Workload Manager for sandbox creation on cache misses and provides JWT-based request signing for secure sandbox communication.\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Requirements\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap and Configuration\n17: \n18: The system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down with support for HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2 (h2c), and optional TLS.\n19: \n20: #### Scenario: Server starts with default configuration\n21: - **GIVEN** a valid router configuration with Port=\"8080\", Debug=false, MaxConcurrentRequests=1000\n22: - **WHEN** `NewServer(config)` is called followed by `Start()`\n23: - **THEN** the HTTP server SHALL bind to the configured port and begin accepting connections with h2c support\n24: \n25: #### Scenario: Server starts with TLS configuration\n26: - **GIVEN** TLS certificate and key files are specified in configuration (TLSCert and TLSKey)\n27: - **WHEN** the server is started with EnableTLS=true\n28: - **THEN** the server SHALL serve HTTPS using the provided certificates\n29: \n30: #### Scenario: Server fails to start with missing TLS cert\n31: - **GIVEN** EnableTLS=true and TLSCert is empty\n32: - **WHEN** `Start()` is called\n33: - **THEN** the server SHALL return an error stating cert/key not provided\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: Server shuts down gracefully\n36: - **GIVEN** a running HTTP server with active connections\n37: - **WHEN** `Shutdown(ctx)` is called with a context timeout of 10 seconds\n38: - **THEN** the server SHALL stop accepting new connections, wait for existing requests to complete within timeout, and release resources\n39: \n40: #### Scenario: Default concurrency limit when zero\n41: - **GIVEN** a configuration with MaxConcurrentRequests=0\n42: - **WHEN** `NewServer(config)` is called\n43: - **THEN** the effective limit SHALL be set to 1000 before route registration\n44: \n45: ---\n46: \n47: ### Requirement: Health and Readiness Endpoints\n48: \n49: The system SHALL expose standard Kubernetes health check endpoints for liveness and readiness probes.\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: Liveness endpoint returns alive\n52: - **GIVEN** the Router HTTP server is running\n53: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/health/live`\n54: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\":\"alive\"}`\n55: \n56: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns ready when session manager available\n57: - **GIVEN** the Router has initialized the session manager\n58: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/health/ready`\n59: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\":\"ready\"}`\n60: \n61: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns not ready when session manager unavailable\n62: - **GIVEN** the Router session manager is nil\n63: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/health/ready`\n64: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 503 with body `{\"status\":\"not ready\",\"error\":\"session manager not available\"}`\n65: \n66: ---\n67: \n68: ### Requirement: Session Resolution and Creation\n69: \n70: The system SHALL resolve sessions from the store by session ID header, or create new sandboxes via the Workload Manager when the header is empty.\n71: \n72: #### Scenario: Missing session triggers workload manager create\n73: - **GIVEN** WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL is set and an invocation request has no `x-agentcube-session-id` header\n74: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySession` runs for AgentRuntimeKind\n75: - **THEN** the client POSTs JSON `{\"kind\":\"AgentRuntime\",\"name\":...,\"namespace\":...}` to `{WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL}/v1/agent-runtime`\n76: \n77: #### Scenario: Existing session loaded from store\n78: - **GIVEN** a request with header `x-agentcube-session-id: sess-abc-123` and the session exists in store\n79: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySession` is called\n80: - **THEN** the system SHALL return the SandboxInfo from store without calling Workload Manager\n81: \n82: #### Scenario: Unknown session returns not found\n83: - **GIVEN** a non-empty session ID not present in store\n84: - **WHEN** the store returns `ErrNotFound`\n85: - **THEN** the error SHALL map to `NewSessionNotFoundError(sessionID)` and the HTTP handler responds using API status (typically 404)\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: Missing WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL fails startup\n88: - **GIVEN** WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL environment variable is unset\n89: - **WHEN** `NewSessionManager` is called\n90: - **THEN** it SHALL return error \"WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL environment variable is not set\"\n91: \n92: #### Scenario: Workload manager auth token attached when available\n93: - **GIVEN** the file `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token` exists and is readable\n94: - **WHEN** the session manager POSTs to Workload Manager\n95: - **THEN** the request SHALL include header `Authorization: Bearer <trimmed contents>`\n96: \n97: #### Scenario: Create response validation\n98: - **GIVEN** workload manager returns HTTP 200 with body `CreateSandboxResponse`\n99: - **WHEN** the session manager handles the response\n100: - **THEN** it SHALL reject with internal error if `sessionId` in body is empty\n101: - **AND** it SHALL build in-memory `SandboxInfo` with `SandboxID`, `Name`, `SessionID`, `EntryPoints` from the response\n102: \n103: #### Scenario: Non-OK from workload manager\n104: - **GIVEN** workload manager returns HTTP 404\n105: - **WHEN** the session manager handles the response\n106: - **THEN** the error SHALL be `NewSandboxTemplateNotFoundError(namespace, name, kind)`\n107: \n108: ---\n109: \n110: ### Requirement: Reverse Proxy to Sandbox\n111: \n112: The system SHALL proxy HTTP requests to sandbox pods with proper URL resolution, header forwarding, and JWT injection.\n113: \n114: #### Scenario: Determine upstream URL from EntryPoints\n115: - **GIVEN** SandboxInfo with EntryPoints containing protocol, endpoint, and path\n116: - **WHEN** upstream URL is determined\n117: - **THEN** the system SHALL match the invocation path prefix against EntryPoints\n118: - **AND** use the first entry point if no match is found\n119: - **AND** build URL by prefixing protocol and \"://\" to endpoint when protocol is set\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: No entry points returns 404\n122: - **GIVEN** SandboxInfo with empty EntryPoints\n123: - **WHEN** upstream is determined\n124: - **THEN** the handler SHALL respond HTTP 404 with JSON `{\"error\":\"no entry point found for sandbox\"}`\n125: \n126: #### Scenario: Path normalization\n127: - **GIVEN** the Gin path param is non-empty and lacks a leading slash\n128: - **WHEN** the proxy Director runs\n129: - **THEN** the outbound path SHALL be prefixed with `/`\n130: \n131: #### Scenario: Forwarding headers set correctly\n132: - **GIVEN** an incoming request with host header\n133: - **WHEN** the proxy Director runs\n134: - **THEN** the system SHALL set:\n135:   - `X-Forwarded-Host` from the incoming request host\n136:   - `X-Forwarded-Proto` to \"https\" when TLS is present else \"http\"\n137:   - `X-Forwarded-For` by appending client IP to any existing values\n138: \n139: #### Scenario: Response header contains session ID\n140: - **GIVEN** a successful proxied request\n141: - **WHEN** the response is returned to client\n142: - **THEN** the response SHALL include header `x-agentcube-session-id` set to the resolved session ID\n143: \n144: ---\n145: \n146: ### Requirement: JWT Injection for Sandbox Authentication\n147: \n148: The system SHALL generate JWT tokens and inject them into proxied requests for sandbox kinds that require authentication.\n149: \n150: #### Scenario: JWT generated for Sandbox kinds\n151: - **GIVEN** a sandbox of kind \"Sandbox\" or \"SandboxClaim\"\n152: - **WHEN** forwarding the request\n153: - **THEN** the system SHALL generate a JWT before proxying\n154: - **AND** set `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on the proxied request\n155: \n156: #### Scenario: JWT signing with RS256\n157: - **GIVEN** a JWTManager with RSA 2048-bit keys\n158: - **WHEN** `GenerateToken` is called with claims `{\"session_id\":\"sess-123\"}`\n159: - **THEN** the token SHALL be signed using RS256 algorithm\n160: - **AND** contain base claims: `exp`, `iat`, `iss=\"agentcube-router\"`\n161: - **AND** merge the custom session_id claim\n162: \n163: #### Scenario: JWT key persistence in Kubernetes secret\n164: - **GIVEN** the Router is running in-cluster\n165: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` is called and secret does not exist\n166: - **THEN** it SHALL create opaque secret `picod-router-identity` in namespace from `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` or \"default\"\n167: - **AND** the secret SHALL contain keys `private.pem` and `public.pem`\n168: \n169: #### Scenario: JWT key loaded from existing secret\n170: - **GIVEN** the secret `picod-router-identity` already exists\n171: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` is called\n172: - **THEN** it SHALL load existing keys from the secret instead of generating new ones\n173: \n174: #### Scenario: Ephemeral keys when not in-cluster\n175: - **GIVEN** the Router is not running in a Kubernetes cluster\n176: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` is called\n177: - **THEN** it SHALL return nil (ephemeral keys will be generated)\n178: - **AND** log a warning about using ephemeral keys\n179: \n180: #### Scenario: JWT signing failure\n181: - **GIVEN** JWT generation returns an error\n182: - **WHEN** forwarding is attempted\n183: - **THEN** the handler SHALL respond HTTP 500 with JSON containing `\"code\":\"JWT_SIGNING_FAILED\"` and `\"error\":\"failed to sign request\"`\n184: \n185: ---\n186: \n187: ### Requirement: Proxy Error Handling\n188: \n189: The system SHALL handle proxy errors gracefully with appropriate HTTP status codes and error messages.\n190: \n191: #### Scenario: Connection refused maps to 502\n192: - **GIVEN** the reverse proxy fails with an error containing \"connection refused\"\n193: - **WHEN** ErrorHandler runs\n194: - **THEN** the response SHALL be HTTP 502 with body `{\"error\":\"sandbox unreachable\"}`\n195: \n196: #### Scenario: Timeout maps to 504\n197: - **GIVEN** the reverse proxy fails with an error containing \"timeout\"\n198: - **WHEN** ErrorHandler runs\n199: - **THEN** the response SHALL be HTTP 504 with body `{\"error\":\"sandbox timeout\"}`\n200: \n201: #### Scenario: Other proxy errors map to 502\n202: - **GIVEN** the reverse proxy fails with any other error\n203: - **WHEN** ErrorHandler runs\n204: - **THEN** the response SHALL be HTTP 502 with body `{\"error\":\"sandbox unreachable\"}`\n205: \n206: ---\n207: \n208: ### Requirement: Last-Activity Tracking\n209: \n210: The system SHALL track session activity by updating the last-activity timestamp in the store.\n211: \n212: #### Scenario: Activity updated on session resolution\n213: - **GIVEN** a request is being processed\n214: - **WHEN** the sandbox is successfully resolved\n215: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `UpdateSessionLastActivity` with `time.Now()`\n216: \n217: #### Scenario: Activity updated after proxy completion\n218: - **GIVEN** a request has been proxied to sandbox\n219: - **WHEN** `forwardToSandbox` returns successfully\n220: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `UpdateSessionLastActivity` with `time.Now()` again\n221: \n222: #### Scenario: Store update failure does not block proxy\n223: - **GIVEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity` returns an error\n224: - **WHEN** handling continues\n225: - **THEN** the proxy SHALL still run if sandbox resolution succeeded\n226: - **AND** the error SHALL be logged as a warning only\n227: \n228: ---\n229: \n230: ### Requirement: Concurrency Limiting\n231: \n232: The system SHALL limit concurrent requests to prevent overload.\n233: \n234: #### Scenario: Request allowed within limit\n235: - **GIVEN** current concurrent requests is below MaxConcurrentRequests\n236: - **WHEN** a new request arrives at a `/v1/*` route\n237: - **THEN** the request SHALL be processed\n238: \n239: #### Scenario: Request rejected when limit exceeded\n240: - **GIVEN** current concurrent requests equals MaxConcurrentRequests\n241: - **WHEN** a new request arrives\n242: - **THEN** the server SHALL respond HTTP 429 with JSON `{\"error\":\"server overloaded, please try again later\",\"code\":\"SERVER_OVERLOADED\"}`\n243: - **AND** abort the request\n244: \n245: #### Scenario: Semaphore released after request completion\n246: - **GIVEN** a request is being processed within the semaphore\n247: - **WHEN** the request completes (success or error)\n248: - **THEN** the semaphore slot SHALL be released for the next request\n249: \n250: ---\n251: \n252: ### Requirement: Invocation Route Registration\n253: \n254: The system SHALL register routes for AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter invocations.\n255: \n256: #### Scenario: AgentRuntime routes registered\n257: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n258: - **WHEN** routes are registered\n259: - **THEN** GET and POST SHALL be registered for `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path`\n260: - **AND** the handler SHALL be `handleAgentInvoke`\n261: \n262: #### Scenario: CodeInterpreter routes registered\n263: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n264: - **WHEN** routes are registered\n265: - **THEN** GET and POST SHALL be registered for `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path`\n266: - **AND** the handler SHALL be `handleCodeInterpreterInvoke`\n267: \n268: #### Scenario: Middleware applied to v1 routes\n269: - **GIVEN** the `/v1/*` route group is created\n270: - **WHEN** routes are registered\n271: - **THEN** the group SHALL have middleware: Gin Logger, Recovery, and ConcurrencyLimit\n272: \n273: #### Scenario: Health endpoints have no middleware\n274: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n275: - **WHEN** routes are registered\n276: - **THEN** `/health/live` and `/health/ready` SHALL have no middleware applied\n277: \n278: ---\n279: \n280: ### Requirement: HTTP Transport Configuration\n281: \n282: The system SHALL configure the HTTP transport for optimal proxy performance.\n283: \n284: #### Scenario: Transport configured with no idle timeout\n285: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n286: - **WHEN** the httpTransport is created\n287: - **THEN** IdleConnTimeout SHALL be 0 (no limit)\n288: - **AND** DisableCompression SHALL be false\n289: - **AND** MaxIdleConnsPerHost SHALL be 100\n290: \n291: #### Scenario: HTTP/2 transport configured\n292: - **GIVEN** the server is initialized\n293: - **WHEN** the transport is configured\n294: - **THEN** `http2.ConfigureTransports` SHALL be called with ReadIdleTimeout: 30s, PingTimeout: 15s\n295: \n296: ---\n297: \n298: ### Requirement: Server Environment Variables\n299: \n300: The system SHALL read configuration from environment variables.\n301: \n302: #### Scenario: WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL required\n303: - **GIVEN** WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL is set to \"http://workload-manager:8080\"\n304: - **WHEN** `NewSessionManager` is called\n305: - **THEN** the session manager SHALL use this URL for sandbox creation\n306: \n307: #### Scenario: AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE for JWT secret\n308: - **GIVEN** AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE is set to \"agentcube-system\"\n309: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` is called\n310: - **THEN** the JWT secret SHALL be created in namespace \"agentcube-system\"\n311: \n312: #### Scenario: Default namespace when AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE unset\n313: - **GIVEN** AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE is not set\n314: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` is called\n315: - **THEN** the JWT secret SHALL be created in namespace \"default\"\n316: \n317: ---\n318: \n319: ### Requirement: CLI Flags\n320: \n321: The system SHALL support command-line flags for configuration.\n322: \n323: #### Scenario: Port flag\n324: - **GIVEN** the `-port` flag is set to \"9090\"\n325: - **WHEN** the server starts\n326: - **THEN** it SHALL listen on port 9090\n327: \n328: #### Scenario: Debug flag enables Gin debug mode\n329: - **GIVEN** the `-debug` flag is set to true\n330: - **WHEN** the server starts\n331: - **THEN** Gin SHALL run in DebugMode\n332: \n333: #### Scenario: TLS flags\n334: - **GIVEN** `-enable-tls=true`, `-tls-cert=/cert.pem`, `-tls-key=/key.pem`\n335: - **WHEN** the server starts\n336: - **THEN** it SHALL serve HTTPS using the provided certificate and key\n337: \n338: #### Scenario: Max concurrent requests flag\n339: - **GIVEN** `-max-concurrent-requests=500`\n340: - **WHEN** the server starts\n341: - **THEN** the concurrency limit SHALL be set to 500\n342: \n343: ---\n344: \n345: ## File Index\n346: \n347: | Path | Purpose |\n348: |------|---------|\n349: | `pkg/router/server.go` | HTTP server setup, Gin engine configuration, route registration |\n350: | `pkg/router/proxy.go` | Reverse proxy implementation with httputil |\n351: | `pkg/router/session_manager.go` | Session resolution and sandbox lookup |\n352: | `pkg/router/jwt.go` | JWT generation and signing (RS256), key management |\n353: | `pkg/router/config.go` | Router configuration types and defaults |\n354: | `pkg/router/handlers.go` | HTTP handler functions for invocations |\n355: | `pkg/router/middleware.go` | Concurrency limiting and custom middleware |\n356: | `pkg/router/health.go` | Health check handlers |\n357: | `pkg/router/metrics.go` | Prometheus metrics for proxy operations |\n358: | `cmd/router/main.go` | Entry point, flag parsing, server lifecycle |\n359: \n360: ---\n361: \n362: ## API Endpoints Summary\n363: \n364: | Method | Path | Description |\n365: |--------|------|-------------|\n366: | GET | `/health/live` | Liveness probe |\n367: | GET | `/health/ready` | Readiness probe |\n368: | GET | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path` | Proxy to AgentRuntime |\n369: | POST | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path` | Proxy to AgentRuntime |\n370: | GET | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path` | Proxy to CodeInterpreter |\n371: | POST | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path` | Proxy to CodeInterpreter |\n372: \n373: ---\n374: \n375: ## Dependencies\n376: \n377: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n378: |------------|---------|---------|\n379: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/store` | Local | Session store interface |\n380: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | Local | SandboxInfo and types |\n381: | `github.com/gin-gonic/gin` | v1.9+ | HTTP framework |\n382: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | v5.x | JWT signing and validation |\n383: | `golang.org/x/net/http2` | Latest | HTTP/2 support |\n384: | `k8s.io/client-go` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes API client |\n385: | `k8s.io/api` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes API types |\n386: | `k8s.io/apimachinery` | v0.34.1 | K8s API machinery |\n387: | `github.com/prometheus/client_golang` | v1.x | Metrics collection |\n388: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | v2.x | Structured logging |\n389: \n390: ---\n391: \n392: ## Constants\n393: \n394: | Name | Value | Description |\n395: |------|-------|-------------|\n396: | `LastActivityAnnotationKey` | `\"agentcube.volcano.sh/last-activity\"` | Annotation key for last activity |\n397: | `rsaKeySize` | `2048` | RSA key size for JWT signing |\n398: | `jwtExpiration` | `5 * time.Minute` | JWT token expiration |\n399: | `IdentitySecretName` | `\"picod-router-identity\"` | Kubernetes secret name for JWT keys |\n400: | `PrivateKeyDataKey` | `\"private.pem\"` | Secret data key for private key |\n401: | `PublicKeyDataKey` | `\"public.pem\"` | Secret data key for public key |\n402: \n403: ---\n404: \n405: ## Default Configuration Values\n406: \n407: | Parameter | Default | Description |\n408: |-----------|---------|-------------|\n409: | `Port` | 8080 | HTTP server port |\n410: | `Debug` | false | Gin debug mode |\n411: | `EnableTLS` | false | Enable TLS termination |\n412: | `MaxConcurrentRequests` | 1000 | Max concurrent proxy requests |\n413: | `ReadTimeout` | 30s | HTTP read timeout |\n414: | `IdleTimeout` | 90s | HTTP idle timeout |\n415: | `ShutdownTimeout` | 10s | Graceful shutdown timeout |\n416: \n417: ---\n418: \n419: ## Environment Variables\n420: \n421: | Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n422: |----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n423: | `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` | Yes | - | Workload Manager base URL |\n424: | `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` | No | \"default\" | Namespace for JWT secret |\n425: \n426: ---\n427: \n428: ## Notes\n429: \n430: - The Router is the edge gateway for AgentCube, handling all invocation traffic\n431: - HTTP/2 support is provided via h2c (HTTP/2 without TLS) for internal communication\n432: - JWT keys are persisted in Kubernetes secrets for pod restart resilience\n433: - Session creation is delegated to the Workload Manager to avoid duplicating orchestration logic\n434: - The Router uses a shared http.Transport for connection pooling and reuse\n435: - WebSocket upgrade is supported via reverse proxy passthrough\n436: - All proxy errors are mapped to 502 or 504 status codes with user-friendly messages\n437: - Last-activity updates are best-effort and do not block the proxy flow\n438: \n439: ---\n440: \n441: *Status: Draft*\n\n(End of file - total 441 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-009: Router HTTP 反向代理核心 - Delta Specification\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-009  \n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n\nImplement the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality in `pkg/router` to route invocation traffic to sandbox pods. The Router serves as the edge gateway for AgentCube, accepting HTTP requests from clients, resolving sessions to sandbox endpoints via the session store, and reverse-proxying traffic to the appropriate sandbox pods. It integrates with the Workload Manager for sandbox creation on cache misses and provides JWT-based request signing for secure sandbox communication.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap and Configuration\n\nThe system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down with support for HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2 (h2c), and optional TLS.\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with default configuration","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775859163838,"end":1775859163861}}}}
